WEBVTT

00:06.048 --> 00:08.675
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:08.675 --> 00:12.387
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:12.387 --> 00:15.057
<i>[rock music]</i>

00:15.057 --> 00:17.935
<i>‐ My name is Chad Bowlin,</i>
<i>and I'm from DeBary, Florida.</i>

00:17.935 --> 00:19.728
When I was five years old,

00:19.728 --> 00:22.022
my dad brought home
"Conan the Barbarian."

00:22.022 --> 00:25.692
<i>After I saw the opening scene</i>
<i>with the forging of the blade,</i>

00:25.692 --> 00:28.195
and I just pointed and said,
"I'm gonna do that."

00:28.195 --> 00:29.696
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:29.696 --> 00:32.407
<i>‐ My name is Cody Myers.</i>
<i>I live in Foxboro, Wisconsin.</i>

00:32.407 --> 00:34.535
My strengths for
a competition like this

00:34.535 --> 00:37.204
lie in the fact that
I'm an instructor.

00:37.204 --> 00:38.288
I've been an instructor
for eight years.

00:38.288 --> 00:40.832
<i>So, having 800 students</i>

00:40.832 --> 00:43.293
<i>having 800 different problems,</i>
<i>things that I've gotta fix</i>

00:43.293 --> 00:46.797
on the fly and come up
with a plan B and make it work.

00:46.797 --> 00:48.215
<i>‐ My name is Doug Butts.</i>

00:48.215 --> 00:50.092
<i>I live in Linden, Alabama.</i>

00:50.092 --> 00:52.552
I worked in the movie industry
for about 25 years.

00:52.552 --> 00:54.721
<i>I started out as a laborer.</i>

00:54.721 --> 00:56.932
<i>From there,</i>
<i>a guy gathered me up</i>

00:56.932 --> 00:59.101
to do some special effects
on a Western,

00:59.101 --> 01:00.894
and I never looked back.

01:00.894 --> 01:02.854
<i>My experience</i>
<i>in special effects, I think,</i>

01:02.854 --> 01:05.649
<i>will come in play</i>
<i>in helping me today.</i>

01:05.649 --> 01:07.693
Well, you have to build it
before you can tear it up.

01:07.693 --> 01:09.736
[laughs]

01:09.736 --> 01:12.781
<i>‐ My name is Ashley Shaw.</i>
<i>I am from Columbus, Ohio.</i>

01:12.781 --> 01:15.784
I have the forge
Rust Wolf Studios.

01:15.784 --> 01:18.245
<i>The Rust Wolf is</i>
<i>this mythic figure</i>

01:18.245 --> 01:19.454
<i>that I've created</i>

01:19.454 --> 01:21.415
<i>that feeds on the bones</i>
<i>of failed projects.</i>

01:21.415 --> 01:23.125
So as I am the Rust Wolf,

01:23.125 --> 01:26.587
with every failure,
I become greater.

01:26.587 --> 01:29.172
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:29.172 --> 01:31.675
You're here to engage
in three timed rounds

01:31.675 --> 01:33.176
of edged‐weapon making
competition

01:33.176 --> 01:35.178
specifically designed
to test every aspect

01:35.178 --> 01:37.764
of your skills in front
of a panel of expert judges

01:37.764 --> 01:39.308
that determines which of you

01:39.308 --> 01:41.351
is our next "Forged in Fire"
champion leaving here

01:41.351 --> 01:43.353
with a check for $10,000.

01:43.353 --> 01:44.604
Up first,

01:44.604 --> 01:47.107
two‐time "Forged in Fire"
champion Ben Abbott.

01:47.107 --> 01:49.484
Next, historic weapons
re‐creation specialist

01:49.484 --> 01:50.819
David Baker.

01:50.819 --> 01:54.823
And last, edged weapons
specialist Doug Marcaida.

01:54.823 --> 01:57.492
Gentlemen, here in The Forge,
we sometimes like to pay homage

01:57.492 --> 01:58.785
to one of our judges.

01:58.785 --> 02:01.872
So today in your first round
of competition,

02:01.872 --> 02:05.292
in an homage to Doug Marcaida,
you'll be making one of these.

02:05.292 --> 02:07.127
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

02:07.127 --> 02:09.629
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:09.629 --> 02:13.800
Actually, two of these:
karambits.

02:13.800 --> 02:15.510
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:15.510 --> 02:17.179
<i>Originating in Southeast Asia,</i>

02:17.179 --> 02:19.348
<i>the karambit is a small,</i>
<i>curved lightweight blade</i>

02:19.348 --> 02:20.599
<i>believed to have been inspired</i>

02:20.599 --> 02:22.684
<i>by the lethal shape</i>
<i>of a tiger's claw.</i>

02:22.684 --> 02:24.269
<i>[tiger roars]</i>

02:24.269 --> 02:26.813
<i>Featuring a unique finger ring</i>
<i>at the end of each handle,</i>

02:26.813 --> 02:28.857
<i>the concealable weapon gives</i>
<i>its user</i>

02:28.857 --> 02:30.651
<i>complete and precise control.</i>

02:30.651 --> 02:32.653
<i>The karambits' nimble design</i>
<i>makes it ideal</i>

02:32.653 --> 02:33.820
<i>for close‐quarters combat,</i>

02:33.820 --> 02:35.989
<i>where it can inflict</i>
<i>lightning‐quick cuts</i>

02:35.989 --> 02:38.784
<i>and hook deep into the flesh.</i>

02:38.784 --> 02:42.162
Doug Marcaida is a specialist
in Filipino martial arts

02:42.162 --> 02:45.332
and the karambit is one
of the tools of his trade.

02:45.332 --> 02:46.833
You will be forging
your karambits

02:46.833 --> 02:48.543
out of 1095 steel.

02:48.543 --> 02:51.505
They must be a matched set,
have all integral construction,

02:51.505 --> 02:53.632
<i>drifted finger holes,</i>
<i>and the blades must be</i>

02:53.632 --> 02:56.343
<i>between 3 1/2 and 4 inches</i>
<i>in length.</i>

02:56.343 --> 02:58.887
You'll have three hours
in which to complete your work.

02:58.887 --> 03:01.014
<i>‐ Having to do two</i>
<i>of any knife,</i>

03:01.014 --> 03:04.685
<i>let alone karambits,</i>
<i>in three hours is obscene.</i>

03:04.685 --> 03:06.645
This is just madness.

03:06.645 --> 03:09.022
‐ In the second round,
you'll refine your karambits

03:09.022 --> 03:11.233
so that we can test them
for strength and durability

03:11.233 --> 03:12.401
in a sheet metal stab,

03:12.401 --> 03:16.071
and for edge retention
in a meat slice.

03:16.071 --> 03:19.032
Gentlemen, I remind you that
after the first round

03:19.032 --> 03:21.243
and your karambits have been
inspected by the judges,

03:21.243 --> 03:23.036
one of you will have
to surrender your blades

03:23.036 --> 03:24.538
and leave The Forge.

03:24.538 --> 03:27.416
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your three hours starts...now.

03:27.416 --> 03:28.500
<i>[metal rock music]</i>

03:28.500 --> 03:30.210
‐ Here we go.

03:30.210 --> 03:33.922
‐ All right, so three hours,
two karambits,

03:33.922 --> 03:36.216
one bar of mono steel.

03:36.216 --> 03:37.884
It's high carbon steel
out there.

03:37.884 --> 03:40.804
Shouldn't be too hard
for these guys

03:40.804 --> 03:42.055
to work that steel, right?

03:42.055 --> 03:44.224
‐ No, the steel is
in a pretty good spot.

03:44.224 --> 03:45.308
Five minutes on blue,

03:45.308 --> 03:47.060
you've got
a good starting billet.

03:47.060 --> 03:48.395
‐ All right,
let's talk to our expert.

03:48.395 --> 03:51.231
Doug Marcaida, you are
a Filipino martial artist.

03:51.231 --> 03:53.900
You grew up with a karambit
clutched in your little claw.

03:53.900 --> 03:55.277
‐ [laughs]
‐ What do you think?

03:55.277 --> 03:58.572
‐ Okay, so, the key feature
about making karambit

03:58.572 --> 04:00.240
is the ring.

04:00.240 --> 04:02.576
<i>If you're gonna put anything</i>
<i>where you're separating</i>

04:02.576 --> 04:04.744
<i>your finger from the rest</i>
<i>of your body,</i>

04:04.744 --> 04:07.747
<i>I mean,</i>
<i>it's gotta be comfortable.</i>

04:07.747 --> 04:09.416
‐ See what we can do with this.

04:09.416 --> 04:10.750
<i>It's two karambits.</i>

04:10.750 --> 04:13.044
<i>Two blades</i>
<i>I've never made before.</i>

04:13.044 --> 04:15.088
My mind is running
a million miles an hour.

04:15.088 --> 04:19.009
<i>Looking at this square stock,</i>
<i>that's a lot of steel to move.</i>

04:19.009 --> 04:22.137
<i>I'm gonna have to use</i>
<i>a power hammer or a press.</i>

04:22.137 --> 04:24.473
I've never used either one
of these tools.

04:24.473 --> 04:28.101
My goal is‐‐is to drive out
the steel as evenly

04:28.101 --> 04:29.770
and efficiently as possible,

04:29.770 --> 04:31.646
<i>enough for two blades,</i>
<i>and cut it in half.</i>

04:31.646 --> 04:34.441
All right, now I gotta
buy one of those.

04:34.441 --> 04:35.650
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:35.650 --> 04:38.111
‐ The steel we are given
for these knives

04:38.111 --> 04:40.781
is <i>a massive block of 1095.</i>

04:40.781 --> 04:43.325
<i>Cutting the steel is gonna</i>
<i>take too long.</i>

04:43.325 --> 04:46.036
I need to work it a bit,
get it more manageable,

04:46.036 --> 04:49.122
<i>and cut a piece that I need</i>
<i>from that.</i>

04:49.122 --> 04:51.958
‐ Ashley's just gonna hammer it
all down flat first.

04:51.958 --> 04:53.794
‐ It makes all the sense
in the world.

04:53.794 --> 04:54.961
Whenever you're drawing
something out,

04:54.961 --> 04:56.296
it's always things
happen at the ends.

04:56.296 --> 04:57.798
‐ Right.

04:57.798 --> 04:59.800
‐ So if you have four ends,
it's twice the annoyance.

04:59.800 --> 05:02.677
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:02.677 --> 05:04.971
<i>‐ I choose to chop my steel</i>
<i>in half</i>

05:04.971 --> 05:07.140
just because the parameters
of two blades‐‐

05:07.140 --> 05:08.892
I felt like
if I could get two pieces

05:08.892 --> 05:10.143
<i>in The Forge at once,</i>

05:10.143 --> 05:13.814
then I'm able to do it
in a quicker fashion.

05:13.814 --> 05:15.816
<i>I'm the only one that</i>
<i>cut my piece in half</i>

05:15.816 --> 05:18.485
to have two pieces
right off the bat.

05:18.485 --> 05:20.070
We'll see how it works out.

05:20.070 --> 05:21.488
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:21.488 --> 05:23.156
<i>‐ I've gotta</i>
<i>think about the handle.</i>

05:23.156 --> 05:25.909
It's integral,
meaning that it's way thicker

05:25.909 --> 05:28.328
than what I'm normally used to
in a knife,

05:28.328 --> 05:31.665
<i>because I'm normally attaching</i>
<i>two scales on the outside.</i>

05:31.665 --> 05:35.252
<i>I'm looking for, you know,</i>
<i>two 9‐inch sections of steel</i>

05:35.252 --> 05:36.837
and make it plenty thick.

05:36.837 --> 05:43.635
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:43.635 --> 05:44.970
‐ Oh.

05:44.970 --> 05:46.513
‐ Well, our smiths are making
quick work

05:46.513 --> 05:48.181
of their high carbon steel
out there.

05:48.181 --> 05:52.185
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:52.185 --> 05:53.353
Bladesmiths!

05:53.353 --> 05:55.105
One hour has elapsed.

05:55.105 --> 05:59.442
You have two hours remaining
to finish your two karambits.

05:59.442 --> 06:00.652
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:00.652 --> 06:03.530
‐ So, my strategy is,
I'm gonna forge out

06:03.530 --> 06:06.074
those finger rings first.

06:06.074 --> 06:08.827
If that handle doesn't fit
comfortably in your hand,

06:08.827 --> 06:10.453
it's basically useless.

06:10.453 --> 06:12.956
Now I've gotta make
two of these things.

06:12.956 --> 06:15.208
<i>So, do the step</i>
<i>on the first one</i>

06:15.208 --> 06:17.544
<i>and then do the same thing</i>
<i>on the second one.</i>

06:17.544 --> 06:19.045
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:19.045 --> 06:21.047
<i>So, I'll drift that punch</i>
<i>through far enough</i>

06:21.047 --> 06:23.592
<i>to where I can finally slide</i>
<i>that hole onto the horn</i>

06:23.592 --> 06:25.552
and then start working it
around.

06:25.552 --> 06:27.262
[clanging]

06:27.262 --> 06:29.764
‐ Well, Cody's really using
the horn and that anvil.

06:29.764 --> 06:34.394
He's working his steel around
the horn as he pounds it round.

06:34.394 --> 06:35.896
‐ You move your piece so that

06:35.896 --> 06:36.855
you're hitting down
all the time.

06:36.855 --> 06:38.732
‐ Ah, interesting.

06:38.732 --> 06:42.569
But if you look at Chad,
Chad's making his blades first.

06:42.569 --> 06:44.279
<i>‐ I forged the tip first.</i>

06:44.279 --> 06:46.907
It's just kind of the way
that I've always forged blades,

06:46.907 --> 06:48.408
and I'm comfortable with that.

06:48.408 --> 06:50.410
<i>I start to forge out,</i>
<i>and I'm thinking,</i>

06:50.410 --> 06:51.786
<i>"I'm gonna make it my style.</i>

06:51.786 --> 06:53.496
<i>I'm gonna give it</i>
<i>a bigger belly on the blade."</i>

06:53.496 --> 06:55.790
<i>So it's not gonna match</i>
<i>exactly</i>

06:55.790 --> 06:57.542
<i>what the judges put up there,</i>

06:57.542 --> 06:59.252
but it should function
very well

06:59.252 --> 07:00.670
<i>in the chopping competition.</i>

07:00.670 --> 07:01.755
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:01.755 --> 07:03.923
‐ I'm looking at Chad's blade,
and Dave,

07:03.923 --> 07:05.425
it kind of looks like

07:05.425 --> 07:07.260
your ring‐handled skinner
over there.

07:07.260 --> 07:09.596
‐ He's got a very large blade
on that thing.

07:09.596 --> 07:11.306
‐ And a belly.
‐ Yeah.

07:11.306 --> 07:12.766
It's kinda going the wrong way.

07:12.766 --> 07:15.644
‐ There many kinds of designs
for karambit blades,

07:15.644 --> 07:19.105
but we've asked for a curve,
a slightly curved inward blade.

07:19.105 --> 07:20.940
<i>‐ I'm trying to remember that</i>
<i>they have match.</i>

07:20.940 --> 07:22.901
<i>They have to pretty much</i>
<i>be as close as they can.</i>

07:22.901 --> 07:25.570
And sometimes I get far enough
on one, I move ahead,

07:25.570 --> 07:28.281
and I realize, "Oh, wait,
they gotta look the same."

07:28.281 --> 07:29.783
You gotta‐‐make one change,
you gotta do it both.

07:29.783 --> 07:31.117
[flame roars]

07:31.117 --> 07:34.120
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

07:34.120 --> 07:37.666
‐ Ashley's working with some
smaller bits of steel.

07:37.666 --> 07:39.250
I don't know
what that's all about.

07:39.250 --> 07:41.461
‐ It just doesn't look like
enough volume for this.

07:41.461 --> 07:43.171
These karambits are
deceptively large.

07:43.171 --> 07:44.130
‐ Yeah.

07:44.130 --> 07:45.590
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:45.590 --> 07:47.801
<i>‐ For these blades,</i>
<i>I'm gonna start with the tip</i>

07:47.801 --> 07:49.135
and work my way back.

07:49.135 --> 07:51.012
Let things fall into place.

07:51.012 --> 07:52.889
[groans]

07:52.889 --> 07:54.307
‐ Any time you make
two of anything,

07:54.307 --> 07:56.184
it gets four times as hard.

07:56.184 --> 07:58.645
<i>‐ It's incredibly difficult</i>
<i>working two blades at once.</i>

07:58.645 --> 08:00.897
You pull one out, work it,
put it back,

08:00.897 --> 08:01.981
<i>pull the other one out...</i>

08:01.981 --> 08:03.817
It's just grueling.

08:03.817 --> 08:05.318
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:05.318 --> 08:09.280
‐ Man, I'm having
more troubles here.

08:09.280 --> 08:10.323
<i>The hole is everything.</i>

08:10.323 --> 08:11.908
[bleep] damn it.

08:11.908 --> 08:15.078
It's gonna have to be done
comfortably and properly.

08:15.078 --> 08:16.371
Come on, baby.

08:16.371 --> 08:18.832
‐ That's a big karambit
Doug's making.

08:18.832 --> 08:21.292
‐ [exhales]
Yeah.

08:21.292 --> 08:23.002
‐ Aw, this ain't working.

08:23.002 --> 08:25.255
<i>I realize I've got</i>
<i>too much metal.</i>

08:25.255 --> 08:28.675
Should have just drawn
the first piece out all the way

08:28.675 --> 08:30.260
<i>and made both knives</i>
<i>out of it.</i>

08:30.260 --> 08:32.178
I'm gonna cut the ends
of 'em off,

08:32.178 --> 08:34.514
get rid of the handles,
and go to it.

08:34.514 --> 08:37.559
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:37.559 --> 08:39.686
‐ It looks like Cody has
moved up to start

08:39.686 --> 08:42.188
fashioning a tip
on one of his karambits.

08:42.188 --> 08:43.940
‐ I started
with the finger rings,

08:43.940 --> 08:45.692
<i>so now I can play around</i>
<i>with my blade</i>

08:45.692 --> 08:47.277
<i>and, like, make sure</i>
<i>I'm within parameters.</i>

08:47.277 --> 08:48.528
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:48.528 --> 08:52.073
The big hurdles coming up
are getting that profile

08:52.073 --> 08:53.700
so that it feels good.

08:53.700 --> 08:54.868
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:54.868 --> 08:56.077
<i>‐ I've got the handle</i>
<i>where I want it.</i>

08:56.077 --> 08:57.495
<i>I've got the tip shaped</i>
<i>where I want it.</i>

08:57.495 --> 09:00.081
Now it's time to start
drifting the hole.

09:00.081 --> 09:02.250
<i>I have drifted holes before</i>
<i>for meat cleavers</i>

09:02.250 --> 09:04.586
and butcher knives,
but I've never drifted a hole

09:04.586 --> 09:06.921
<i>large enough for your finger.</i>

09:06.921 --> 09:07.922
There we go.

09:07.922 --> 09:09.382
<i>If you don't drift it well,</i>

09:09.382 --> 09:11.092
<i>I mean, you could actually</i>
<i>knock part of the steel</i>

09:11.092 --> 09:14.095
<i>off to the side;</i>
<i>you get an inclusion into it.</i>

09:14.095 --> 09:16.222
<i>Sometimes it doesn't punch</i>
<i>right and you end up</i>

09:16.222 --> 09:18.016
<i>tearing off more material</i>
<i>than you wanted,</i>

09:18.016 --> 09:19.893
and you have
to start over again.

09:19.893 --> 09:21.728
You lose the back half
of your knife.

09:21.728 --> 09:25.023
‐ Chad is now working to get
his rings in place.

09:25.023 --> 09:27.901
‐ Right, but the problem is,
that hole isn't offset.

09:27.901 --> 09:29.736
It's dead in line
with the points.

09:29.736 --> 09:32.280
‐ When you make a wrist,
your hand is not straight.

09:32.280 --> 09:33.448
‐ Right.

09:33.448 --> 09:34.616
‐ So when you put something
in there,

09:34.616 --> 09:36.284
it's not gonna fit
comfortably in there.

09:36.284 --> 09:37.577
‐ Bladesmiths!

09:37.577 --> 09:41.414
You have one hour remaining
to finish your work.

09:41.414 --> 09:45.001
‐ Wil screaming the time
sends chills down my spine.

09:45.001 --> 09:46.211
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:46.211 --> 09:47.962
<i>The hardest thing</i>
<i>in blacksmithing is</i>

09:47.962 --> 09:49.631
<i>to make two things the same.</i>

09:49.631 --> 09:50.757
[laughs]

09:50.757 --> 09:53.927
One's hard enough,
and now we got two.

09:53.927 --> 09:55.970
<i>The curves in the blade</i>
<i>are difficult.</i>

09:55.970 --> 09:58.431
<i>They need to match,</i>
<i>so, you know,</i>

09:58.431 --> 10:01.976
it just adds another element
of difficulty.

10:01.976 --> 10:04.813
‐ I do like that Doug has taken
both of his knives

10:04.813 --> 10:07.941
over to the examples
and lined them up.

10:07.941 --> 10:10.401
‐ All right, Douglas,
think about what you're doing.

10:10.401 --> 10:11.778
Concentrate, son.

10:11.778 --> 10:14.447
4 1/2, baby,
that's where I wanna be.

10:14.447 --> 10:16.950
‐ I'm a little bit worried
about Ashley.

10:16.950 --> 10:18.785
He's got really short pieces
of steel,

10:18.785 --> 10:20.245
he doesn't have defined tips,

10:20.245 --> 10:23.957
he doesn't have any defined
finger rings at this point.

10:23.957 --> 10:25.458
<i>‐ I've made few karambits.</i>

10:25.458 --> 10:28.128
Usually, I took a shortcut
and started with a wrench

10:28.128 --> 10:29.963
that already had a hole
for the finger.

10:29.963 --> 10:32.006
<i>So this is an added level</i>
<i>of difficulty‐‐</i>

10:32.006 --> 10:33.591
<i>having to drift one myself.</i>

10:33.591 --> 10:35.301
That ain't good.

10:35.301 --> 10:37.178
<i>I'm running into issues.</i>

10:37.178 --> 10:39.139
I'm not punching through
the steel

10:39.139 --> 10:41.182
<i>as quickly as I would like.</i>

10:41.182 --> 10:44.727
It's time‐consuming.
I'm getting tired.

10:44.727 --> 10:45.812
<i>It's a mess.</i>

10:45.812 --> 10:47.480
‐ Man.
‐ Damn.

10:47.480 --> 10:49.983
‐ I think Ashley's
in big trouble, man.

10:49.983 --> 10:51.401
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:51.401 --> 10:53.820
‐ If I don't get this
finger hole drifted properly

10:53.820 --> 10:56.322
and comfortable,
I could go home.

10:56.322 --> 10:58.199
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:02.745 --> 11:03.997
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:03.997 --> 11:05.957
‐ Ashley's hammering a spike

11:05.957 --> 11:08.543
into an evil
metal vampire, man.

11:08.543 --> 11:10.253
That is a huge drift.

11:10.253 --> 11:12.422
‐ And a really small
piece of steel.

11:12.422 --> 11:14.382
<i>‐ It comes to a point</i>
<i>where I get them</i>

11:14.382 --> 11:15.884
good enough for now.

11:15.884 --> 11:19.262
<i>[metal rock music]</i>

11:19.262 --> 11:20.889
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:20.889 --> 11:23.516
I've got 33 minutes
and some change,

11:23.516 --> 11:26.060
<i>and I've got a lot of grinding</i>
<i>and a quench to get through.</i>

11:26.060 --> 11:28.146
I'm feeling like
I can get there.

11:28.146 --> 11:31.107
‐ Bladesmiths!
30 minutes!

11:31.107 --> 11:34.068
<i>‐ There's 30 minutes left</i>
<i>and I know I have to quench.</i>

11:34.068 --> 11:36.321
Everything's riding
on this quench,

11:36.321 --> 11:38.865
<i>so I gotta get it right.</i>

11:38.865 --> 11:41.576
‐ So, Doug just quenched
one of his karambits.

11:41.576 --> 11:43.578
‐ No warpage at all.
I'm thrilled.

11:43.578 --> 11:46.331
<i>Second knife, no warpage.</i>

11:46.331 --> 11:48.124
<i>I've got quenched,</i>
<i>hardened blades.</i>

11:48.124 --> 11:49.375
<i>My holes are there.</i>

11:49.375 --> 11:51.836
‐ Doug is really killing it
right now.

11:51.836 --> 11:54.297
He's kinda out ahead
of the crowd, I'd say.

11:54.297 --> 11:55.924
‐ Oh, way ahead.
‐ Oh, I agree.

11:55.924 --> 11:57.508
[machinery whirring]

11:57.508 --> 11:58.718
‐ 15 minutes!

11:58.718 --> 12:00.261
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:00.261 --> 12:02.347
‐ I know the heat treat's
not something that

12:02.347 --> 12:03.765
I can skimp on.

12:03.765 --> 12:05.183
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:05.183 --> 12:06.684
<i>If you don't have</i>
<i>a good heat treat,</i>

12:06.684 --> 12:08.770
it's basically a letter opener.

12:08.770 --> 12:11.522
<i>First one skates beautifully.</i>

12:11.522 --> 12:14.609
Now I've gotta go and do
the exact same thing again.

12:14.609 --> 12:20.823
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:20.823 --> 12:23.534
So I've got two hardened,
straight blades.

12:23.534 --> 12:24.994
<i>I've got a few minutes</i>
<i>to kill.</i>

12:24.994 --> 12:28.122
You know, I don't want
to mess with the blade

12:28.122 --> 12:29.499
<i>until it's been tempered.</i>

12:29.499 --> 12:31.209
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:31.209 --> 12:33.628
‐ Five minutes, bladesmiths!

12:33.628 --> 12:35.797
<i>‐ At this point,</i>
<i>both blades are hardened.</i>

12:35.797 --> 12:38.258
<i>They're on the anvil.</i>
<i>It's not a typical karambit.</i>

12:38.258 --> 12:39.592
It's kind of my take
on the karambit,

12:39.592 --> 12:40.969
so it's a unique look to it.

12:40.969 --> 12:42.762
<i>So I think they might</i>
<i>like that.</i>

12:42.762 --> 12:44.389
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:44.389 --> 12:47.058
<i>‐ I go in for my quench.</i>
<i>All's quiet.</i>

12:47.058 --> 12:49.686
I'm not feeling any weird pops
or tings in the steel.

12:49.686 --> 12:51.312
<i>Set it down to cool,</i>

12:51.312 --> 12:54.232
<i>and I'm on</i>
<i>to my next karambit.</i>

12:54.232 --> 12:56.234
As soon as I've got
my blades quenched

12:56.234 --> 12:58.945
and cooled down to handle,
it's back to the grinder.

12:58.945 --> 13:01.948
I need to get it looking like
a knife, not like an oily mess.

13:01.948 --> 13:04.075
<i>[exciting rock music]</i>

13:04.075 --> 13:05.410
‐ Ten seconds!

13:05.410 --> 13:06.577
‐ That one's good.

13:06.577 --> 13:07.870
This one I got, like,
a little carried away.

13:07.870 --> 13:10.832
‐ Five, four, three,

13:10.832 --> 13:13.001
two, one...

13:13.001 --> 13:14.752
Bladesmiths, shut down
your machines, drop your tools.

13:14.752 --> 13:19.382
This first round of karambit
competition is over.

13:19.382 --> 13:20.383
‐ Whoo!
[applause]

13:20.383 --> 13:23.011
‐ That was a good one.
‐ [whistles]

13:23.011 --> 13:24.429
‐ Don't be whooping yet.

13:24.429 --> 13:28.099
‐ My blades are done.
Whoo!

13:28.099 --> 13:30.226
[laughs]

13:30.226 --> 13:33.229
‐ Bladesmiths, this first round
of competition is complete.

13:33.229 --> 13:35.356
Now it's time for the judges
to take a closer look

13:35.356 --> 13:36.357
at your karambits.

13:36.357 --> 13:37.608
You had to have a match pair

13:37.608 --> 13:40.320
with drifted finger rings,
integral handles,

13:40.320 --> 13:43.740
and 3 to 4 1/2‐inch
karambit blades.

13:43.740 --> 13:44.907
Ashley, you're up first.

13:44.907 --> 13:47.326
Please present your blades
to the judges.

13:47.326 --> 13:49.787
<i>[tense music]</i>

13:49.787 --> 13:52.790
<i>‐ All right, Ashley,</i>
<i>so one of them</i>

13:52.790 --> 13:54.500
is on its way to being
the right way

13:54.500 --> 13:55.585
a karambit should be held.

13:55.585 --> 13:57.545
It's comfortable
when you grab onto it.

13:57.545 --> 14:00.339
You can tell where the edge is,
and it's got that curve,

14:00.339 --> 14:02.717
that hook that
we're looking for.

14:02.717 --> 14:04.886
And this blade
is pretty much straight up,

14:04.886 --> 14:06.971
and look what happens
to my hand.

14:06.971 --> 14:09.766
See how this pulls up?
It pushes my finger away.

14:09.766 --> 14:11.893
That puts a lot of stress
on my whole hand.

14:11.893 --> 14:14.437
If you move you forward,
there are ways

14:14.437 --> 14:17.732
of either curving this inward
or pulling it back

14:17.732 --> 14:20.234
so that it gets comfortable
to where I can just grab on

14:20.234 --> 14:22.737
and then align my hands
back in again.

14:22.737 --> 14:24.655
The key about having
these blades is,

14:24.655 --> 14:26.282
can you make a natural fist?

14:26.282 --> 14:27.784
Think about, like,
if you're a boxer.

14:27.784 --> 14:29.869
These are just extensions
of what you have in your hand.

14:29.869 --> 14:31.788
<i>[dramatic percussion]</i>

14:31.788 --> 14:33.039
‐ All right, Doug, you're up.

14:33.039 --> 14:34.916
Please present your karambits
to the judges.

14:34.916 --> 14:36.793
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:36.793 --> 14:38.211
<i>‐ The first thing that</i>
<i>strikes me</i>

14:38.211 --> 14:40.880
<i>when I pick these up</i>
<i>is the length of the handle.</i>

14:40.880 --> 14:43.549
I've got two inches
of extra handle here

14:43.549 --> 14:44.967
on both of them, equally.

14:44.967 --> 14:46.010
You know, 'cause you did

14:46.010 --> 14:47.720
a very good job of making
a match set.

14:47.720 --> 14:48.805
‐ Yes.

14:48.805 --> 14:50.098
‐ And the other thing is,

14:50.098 --> 14:52.308
this ring is directly in line
with the center.

14:52.308 --> 14:54.060
And you can see what that does

14:54.060 --> 14:55.770
to me trying to hold
this thing,

14:55.770 --> 14:57.563
but you're well on your way.

14:57.563 --> 14:59.190
Nice job.
‐ Thank you.

14:59.190 --> 15:01.359
‐ All right, Cody,
you ready for this?

15:01.359 --> 15:02.568
‐ Believe so.

15:02.568 --> 15:04.278
‐ Please present your blades
to the judges.

15:04.278 --> 15:05.571
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:05.571 --> 15:08.241
<i>‐ Right off,</i>
<i>these things weigh a ton.</i>

15:08.241 --> 15:09.325
‐ Yeah, they're beefcakes.

15:09.325 --> 15:10.910
‐ [laughs]

15:10.910 --> 15:13.204
The finger alignment
on that one's real close.

15:13.204 --> 15:14.539
Not so much on this one.

15:14.539 --> 15:17.500
So there's a lot of material
to remove on these

15:17.500 --> 15:20.044
as well as to get
that shape refined.

15:20.044 --> 15:22.880
But I think you're well
on your way.

15:22.880 --> 15:25.216
‐ Thank you, sir.
‐ All right, Chad, you're up.

15:25.216 --> 15:27.176
Please present your work
to the judges.

15:27.176 --> 15:29.512
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:29.512 --> 15:31.013
<i>‐ All right, Chad.</i>

15:31.013 --> 15:33.724
We're looking for the inward
curve of the blade

15:33.724 --> 15:36.978
to signify and give
that essence of a karambit:

15:36.978 --> 15:39.480
to be something that's a claw
that can hook into you,

15:39.480 --> 15:42.024
that can dig in when
you're fighting with that.

15:42.024 --> 15:45.027
I do not see that here.
You have the handle for that.

15:45.027 --> 15:48.656
What I see is almost
like a skinner with a ring.

15:48.656 --> 15:50.324
That's not what
we're looking for.

15:50.324 --> 15:51.742
‐ Okay.

15:51.742 --> 15:53.911
‐ All right, Chad, obviously,
there's a big problem.

15:53.911 --> 15:55.371
We asked for a karambit.

15:55.371 --> 15:58.124
That's not what
we're looking at here.

15:58.124 --> 16:00.501
So at this time,
I have to ask you

16:00.501 --> 16:01.460
to please leave The Forge.
‐ Okay.

16:01.460 --> 16:04.213
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

16:04.213 --> 16:05.423
<i>‐ What I turned in</i>

16:05.423 --> 16:06.924
<i>was my interpretation</i>
<i>of a karambit.</i>

16:06.924 --> 16:08.384
Thank you, sir.

16:08.384 --> 16:10.386
If I had it to do over again,

16:10.386 --> 16:11.971
<i>I would have paid</i>
<i>more attention</i>

16:11.971 --> 16:13.598
<i>to the actual blade style,</i>

16:13.598 --> 16:16.184
and it was an easy correction
I could have made.

16:16.184 --> 16:18.686
<i>I feel that I actually have</i>
<i>the ability</i>

16:18.686 --> 16:19.979
<i>to continue on this path.</i>

16:19.979 --> 16:21.522
I want to continue to grow.

16:21.522 --> 16:23.733
And the judges said
I made a great skinner,

16:23.733 --> 16:25.359
for what it's worth.

16:25.359 --> 16:28.404
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:28.404 --> 16:29.655
‐ Bladesmiths, congratulations.

16:29.655 --> 16:31.199
You've made it
in the second round

16:31.199 --> 16:32.450
of this competition.

16:32.450 --> 16:33.784
And now that your karambits
are tempered,

16:33.784 --> 16:35.536
it's time to make them
fully functional,

16:35.536 --> 16:38.873
adding flint‐knap texturing
to your handles

16:38.873 --> 16:40.791
and cleaning up those
finger rings.

16:40.791 --> 16:42.251
You'll have one hour
in this round

16:42.251 --> 16:43.586
in which to complete
your work.

16:43.586 --> 16:45.546
<i>‐ Only having an hour</i>
<i>in the second round</i>

16:45.546 --> 16:47.506
brings my stress to the roof.

16:47.506 --> 16:49.008
<i>‐ One hour?</i>

16:49.008 --> 16:51.260
I could spend an hour
just sharpening that thing.

16:51.260 --> 16:52.762
‐ After this round,

16:52.762 --> 16:54.096
your weapons will be tested
for strength

16:54.096 --> 16:56.807
and durability
in a sheet metal stab,

16:56.807 --> 17:00.186
and for edge retention
in a meat slice.

17:00.186 --> 17:01.479
Bladesmiths, I remind you

17:01.479 --> 17:02.855
that after your blades
have been tested,

17:02.855 --> 17:05.107
one of you will be asked
to surrender your karambits

17:05.107 --> 17:06.317
and leave The Forge.

17:06.317 --> 17:09.820
Good luck.
Your one hour starts...now.

17:09.820 --> 17:11.906
<i>[rock music]</i>

17:11.906 --> 17:13.616
‐ Ha, we've never hit smiths

17:13.616 --> 17:15.326
with a one‐hour time frame
before.

17:15.326 --> 17:18.287
‐ I think these guys are gonna
be genuinely surprised

17:18.287 --> 17:19.997
with what they can accomplish
in an hour.

17:19.997 --> 17:21.749
‐ I'm stressing big time.

17:21.749 --> 17:24.335
<i>For two knives, I've got</i>
<i>eight different bevels;</i>

17:24.335 --> 17:25.962
<i>I've got four different edges.</i>

17:25.962 --> 17:28.130
This is absolutely ludicrous
to do in one hour.

17:28.130 --> 17:30.424
‐ One thing I want to see
from everyone here

17:30.424 --> 17:33.135
is some Dremel work
in those rings.

17:33.135 --> 17:34.637
'Cause a lot of the stress
will be transferred

17:34.637 --> 17:35.846
on your index fingers.

17:35.846 --> 17:38.349
<i>‐ My game plan is,</i>
<i>get to the grinder.</i>

17:38.349 --> 17:41.477
<i>That's where I'm gonna be,</i>
<i>and I'm not gonna go far.</i>

17:41.477 --> 17:43.563
‐ I got one hour‐‐
less than one hour.

17:43.563 --> 17:44.814
I'm freaking out.

17:44.814 --> 17:47.441
‐ Doug's got some cutting
and welding to do, yes?

17:47.441 --> 17:49.360
‐ Yeah, if I were Doug,
I would cut two inches

17:49.360 --> 17:52.238
out of that handle he's got,
rotate the ring,

17:52.238 --> 17:54.323
and put it in the correct spot,
and weld it all back together.

17:54.323 --> 17:56.826
<i>‐ I have to remove</i>
<i>the ring first,</i>

17:56.826 --> 17:59.537
and I've gotta lose an inch
out of the handle,

17:59.537 --> 18:01.831
<i>and then weld 'em</i>
<i>back together.</i>

18:01.831 --> 18:03.457
<i>I'm worried about my temper,</i>

18:03.457 --> 18:06.961
<i>so I'm gonna weld one side</i>
<i>at a time on each knife</i>

18:06.961 --> 18:09.255
<i>and spread it out to where</i>
<i>I don't put too much heat</i>

18:09.255 --> 18:10.881
<i>into the knife at once.</i>

18:10.881 --> 18:14.176
And I'm truly just gonna
have to hope for the best.

18:14.176 --> 18:15.803
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

18:15.803 --> 18:17.555
<i>‐ Only having an hour to get</i>
<i>through all the fit and finish</i>

18:17.555 --> 18:19.265
on two blades is
maddening enough.

18:19.265 --> 18:20.808
<i>It would have been hard</i>
<i>even if I had</i>

18:20.808 --> 18:22.893
<i>come in with two perfectly</i>
<i>prepared blades.</i>

18:22.893 --> 18:24.770
Well, the first thing
I've gotta do is get

18:24.770 --> 18:26.939
<i>that second stumpy handle</i>
<i>a little bit longer.</i>

18:26.939 --> 18:29.317
‐ Now, it looks to me like
Ashley's cut the ring off

18:29.317 --> 18:31.027
and is just gonna add
some material in

18:31.027 --> 18:32.069
to beef it up.
‐ Ah, okay.

18:32.069 --> 18:34.071
<i>‐ I'm cutting out</i>
<i>an extra piece</i>

18:34.071 --> 18:35.781
<i>that I'm gonna weld in there</i>
<i>to give it some extra length.</i>

18:35.781 --> 18:40.077
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:40.077 --> 18:41.787
Ah, [bleep].

18:41.787 --> 18:43.372
I've got some gaps
in my handle,

18:43.372 --> 18:46.584
and it's just not stacking up
right.

18:46.584 --> 18:48.085
<i>If I don't get</i>
<i>this weld right,</i>

18:48.085 --> 18:49.587
<i>it could break off.</i>

18:49.587 --> 18:51.922
<i>If my knife breaks,</i>
<i>I'm going home.</i>

18:55.635 --> 18:57.219
‐ I had difficulty
with my first weld.

18:57.219 --> 18:59.138
I'm not a welder.

18:59.138 --> 19:00.931
<i>I gotta head back over</i>
<i>and clean up the job.</i>

19:00.931 --> 19:02.433
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:02.433 --> 19:04.852
<i>Second try at the welder,</i>
<i>everything's going great.</i>

19:04.852 --> 19:06.979
<i>I'm making progress,</i>
<i>but it's wasted time</i>

19:06.979 --> 19:08.022
<i>that I don't have.</i>

19:08.022 --> 19:11.651
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:11.651 --> 19:13.486
<i>‐ Now I'm starting to set</i>
<i>that profile in,</i>

19:13.486 --> 19:15.488
so that hand fits nice
in the blade,

19:15.488 --> 19:18.199
<i>and then come in and put that</i>
<i>flint‐knapping texture in.</i>

19:18.199 --> 19:20.159
‐ Cody, man,
he's really committed

19:20.159 --> 19:23.954
to just refining
his shape on that grinder.

19:23.954 --> 19:26.457
<i>‐ When you flint‐knap stone</i>
<i>into blade,</i>

19:26.457 --> 19:29.168
you're basically chiseling away
at that material,

19:29.168 --> 19:31.921
<i>and it comes out with</i>
<i>all these little grooves.</i>

19:31.921 --> 19:35.466
<i>So this is mimicking that</i>
<i>same look, that same texture.</i>

19:35.466 --> 19:37.259
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:37.259 --> 19:39.512
‐ Ashley's extended his handle,
but he hasn't moved that ring.

19:39.512 --> 19:41.013
‐ Yeah.
‐ It's too straight up.

19:41.013 --> 19:43.265
‐ That hand should be able
to line up

19:43.265 --> 19:44.892
just the way your hand is
when it's closed.

19:44.892 --> 19:47.520
Those grooves, those holes
shouldn't pull a finger

19:47.520 --> 19:48.688
in any direction.

19:48.688 --> 19:50.690
‐ I feel decent
about my finger rings.

19:50.690 --> 19:52.149
<i>I've got that length</i>
<i>that I need.</i>

19:52.149 --> 19:54.360
<i>I'm working on the texturing</i>
<i>in both of my handles.</i>

19:54.360 --> 19:56.696
‐ You have just 30 minutes
remaining in the round!

19:56.696 --> 19:57.905
‐ I love it.

19:57.905 --> 19:59.907
<i>I got 23 minutes left.</i>

19:59.907 --> 20:02.201
I'd like to get 'em
a little bit more refined

20:02.201 --> 20:05.037
<i>on the blade slide</i>
<i>and sharpened.</i>

20:05.037 --> 20:06.372
<i>I love these grinders,</i>

20:06.372 --> 20:09.041
<i>but they take a awful lot</i>
<i>of meat really fast.</i>

20:09.041 --> 20:12.044
‐ One of Doug's blades gets
really narrow.

20:12.044 --> 20:14.004
‐ Yeah.
‐ Hopefully, it'll be okay.

20:14.004 --> 20:15.339
<i>‐ I wish they could</i>
<i>be prettier,</i>

20:15.339 --> 20:18.426
but there's just not
a lot of time.

20:18.426 --> 20:19.677
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:19.677 --> 20:22.054
‐ Does Cody have any Dremels
inside his rings?

20:22.054 --> 20:24.223
‐ I don't think he's left
that grinder.

20:24.223 --> 20:27.226
<i>‐ One of my finger rings</i>
<i>isn't a perfect circle,</i>

20:27.226 --> 20:29.270
and it's not
a comfortable feeling.

20:29.270 --> 20:31.856
<i>If I had more time,</i>
<i>I would get inside that ring</i>

20:31.856 --> 20:35.234
either with a Dremel or
file set and clean that out

20:35.234 --> 20:37.361
and make sure it was
a nice, circular profile.

20:37.361 --> 20:39.196
<i>I basically have</i>
<i>no time left,</i>

20:39.196 --> 20:40.740
<i>and I gotta get</i>
<i>these blades sharp.</i>

20:40.740 --> 20:43.784
So I'm just kinda [bleep]
bricks at the moment.

20:43.784 --> 20:45.578
<i>‐ Doug is gonna do</i>
<i>his flint knapping</i>

20:45.578 --> 20:46.662
<i>with an angle grinder.</i>

20:46.662 --> 20:47.830
‐ That's one way to do it.

20:47.830 --> 20:49.290
It's gotta be regular
and it has to have

20:49.290 --> 20:51.375
an interesting appearance.

20:51.375 --> 20:53.544
<i>‐ Flint‐knapping is something</i>
<i>I've never done,</i>

20:53.544 --> 20:56.088
<i>so I'm a little nervous</i>
<i>about it.</i>

20:56.088 --> 20:57.798
<i>I have no idea</i>
<i>how it's gonna test‐‐</i>

20:57.798 --> 21:00.926
you know, I think well
if I can get an edge on here.

21:00.926 --> 21:03.929
<i>Not much time.</i>
<i>Freaking out.</i>

21:03.929 --> 21:06.599
‐ Five minutes, bladesmiths.
Five minutes!

21:06.599 --> 21:07.933
<i>[exciting rock music]</i>

21:07.933 --> 21:09.935
<i>‐ The most important part</i>
<i>about this blade is</i>

21:09.935 --> 21:12.104
it's gotta be
a deadly fearsome edge.

21:12.104 --> 21:15.483
If it doesn't cut,
it's not a karambit.

21:15.483 --> 21:17.902
<i>It needs to be sharp,</i>
<i>but it needs to be strong.</i>

21:17.902 --> 21:20.780
<i>I'm worried that I've brought</i>
<i>my tips very fine.</i>

21:20.780 --> 21:23.783
I'm worried they'll snap off
in the metal pierce.

21:23.783 --> 21:26.410
<i>But now I need to focus</i>
<i>on my finger holes.</i>

21:26.410 --> 21:27.912
<i>I need to get them smooth.</i>

21:27.912 --> 21:29.246
‐ I've never built two knives

21:29.246 --> 21:30.956
in four hours ever
in my life, so...

21:30.956 --> 21:33.959
‐ A testament of will.
‐ That's it, baby.

21:33.959 --> 21:35.628
<i>‐ I'm sliding</i>
<i>the finger rings on,</i>

21:35.628 --> 21:36.796
<i>making sure they fit.</i>

21:36.796 --> 21:38.506
<i>One's a little tighter</i>
<i>than other,</i>

21:38.506 --> 21:39.632
but I think it feels good.

21:39.632 --> 21:44.762
‐ Five, four, three,
two, one...

21:44.762 --> 21:46.222
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines,

21:46.222 --> 21:47.473
drop your tools.

21:47.473 --> 21:50.351
This second round
of karambit creation is over.

21:50.351 --> 21:52.102
‐ Whoo!

21:52.102 --> 21:54.480
We're done.
[chuckles] Oh, wow.

21:54.480 --> 21:56.690
‐ Man.
‐ Way to pull it out.

21:56.690 --> 22:00.110
These four hours smoked me.
[laughs]

22:00.110 --> 22:02.655
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to the strength test.

22:02.655 --> 22:04.615
To test the strength
and durability of your edge

22:04.615 --> 22:06.617
as well as the overall
construction of your karambits,

22:06.617 --> 22:07.993
I'll be taking them
and bashing them

22:07.993 --> 22:10.496
into these steel plates,

22:10.496 --> 22:11.872
then stabbing them
into the wood

22:11.872 --> 22:13.457
to test for tip retention.

22:13.457 --> 22:15.334
You all have to exit
the strength test

22:15.334 --> 22:17.253
with a functioning pair
of karambits.

22:17.253 --> 22:18.671
Ashley, you're up first.
You ready?

22:18.671 --> 22:20.172
‐ I dare ya.
Do it.

22:20.172 --> 22:21.507
‐ [laughs]
Dare me?

22:21.507 --> 22:22.883
All right.

22:22.883 --> 22:25.177
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

22:25.177 --> 22:29.265
<i>‐ I feel like I could faint.</i>
<i>This is terrifying.</i>

22:29.265 --> 22:31.642
<i>It's like seeing</i>
<i>your child try</i>

22:31.642 --> 22:33.686
and take a knife
to a toaster.

22:33.686 --> 22:38.983
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:38.983 --> 22:40.568
[exhales]

22:40.568 --> 22:43.487
<i>[rock music]</i>

22:43.487 --> 22:46.615
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:46.615 --> 22:48.242
[laughs]

22:48.242 --> 22:53.873
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:53.873 --> 22:55.207
<i>[dramatic percussion]</i>

22:55.207 --> 22:57.668
‐ Well, that's karambit one.

22:57.668 --> 22:59.378
You ready for me to test
karambit two?

22:59.378 --> 23:01.547
‐ [sighs] Might as well.
We're this far.

23:01.547 --> 23:02.882
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:02.882 --> 23:04.592
<i>Ben's having trouble</i>
<i>with one of the rings</i>

23:04.592 --> 23:05.843
<i>on my karambits.</i>

23:05.843 --> 23:08.387
<i>I'm freaking out.</i>

23:08.387 --> 23:11.390
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

23:11.390 --> 23:16.395
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:16.395 --> 23:18.439
<i>[echoing percussion]</i>

23:18.439 --> 23:23.360
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:23.360 --> 23:26.697
<i>[echoing percussion]</i>

23:26.697 --> 23:29.158
‐ Well, Ashley,
first things first:

23:29.158 --> 23:30.910
on both of your karambits,

23:30.910 --> 23:33.871
they lost a tip
in the tip retention test.

23:33.871 --> 23:36.081
But the big issue I have
is the size and position

23:36.081 --> 23:37.583
of this hole.

23:37.583 --> 23:39.585
It caused me to not be able
to make a comfortable fist.

23:39.585 --> 23:42.671
I had to readjust, using
just the tip of my finger,

23:42.671 --> 23:44.590
which, as you can see,
rotates that blade

23:44.590 --> 23:45.591
by 90 degrees.

23:45.591 --> 23:46.926
But all in all,

23:46.926 --> 23:49.136
you have two karambits
coming out of this test.

23:49.136 --> 23:50.262
Well done.
‐ Thank you.

23:50.262 --> 23:51.931
‐ Doug, how you feeling?

23:51.931 --> 23:53.766
‐ After that,
I'm a little nervous.

23:53.766 --> 23:54.934
‐ [laughs]

23:54.934 --> 23:56.727
Well, we're gonna do it
anyway.

23:56.727 --> 23:58.103
<i>[tense music]</i>

23:58.103 --> 24:00.230
<i>‐ Gosh, sheet metal.</i>

24:00.230 --> 24:03.609
<i>[exhales, laughs] You just</i>
<i>don't do that to knives.</i>

24:03.609 --> 24:05.235
<i>I know that there's</i>
<i>a good chance</i>

24:05.235 --> 24:06.612
<i>my blades are gonna break.</i>

24:06.612 --> 24:08.739
I mean, his tips came off.
Why shouldn't mine?

24:08.739 --> 24:11.283
<i>[intense rock music]</i>

24:11.283 --> 24:18.290
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:38.978 --> 24:40.771
<i>[tense music]</i>

24:40.771 --> 24:43.190
‐ Well, Doug, I liked that
you shortened your handles

24:43.190 --> 24:46.110
and changed the positioning
of your rings.

24:46.110 --> 24:47.903
They could still be shorter,
though.

24:47.903 --> 24:50.155
Underneath my hand,
there is a good inch and a half

24:50.155 --> 24:52.825
in between where my hand is
and where the blade starts.

24:52.825 --> 24:55.494
And it was difficult to control
because of the length of this.

24:55.494 --> 24:57.162
But more importantly,
in the strength test,

24:57.162 --> 24:59.665
<i>both of your tips took damage</i>
<i>from the steel.</i>

24:59.665 --> 25:01.500
But all in all,
you're walking away

25:01.500 --> 25:03.002
with two karambits.

25:03.002 --> 25:04.962
Well done.
‐ Thank you, sir.

25:04.962 --> 25:06.672
‐ Cody, you're up.
You ready for this?

25:06.672 --> 25:08.841
‐ Give her hell.
‐ All right.

25:08.841 --> 25:10.676
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

25:10.676 --> 25:12.302
<i>‐ I feel like my blades are</i>
<i>in good shape,</i>

25:12.302 --> 25:14.680
<i>but it's a hard, hard test.</i>

25:14.680 --> 25:17.933
<i>This is meant to push</i>
<i>these blades to their limit.</i>

25:17.933 --> 25:20.644
<i>[exciting rock music]</i>

25:20.644 --> 25:27.609
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:49.882 --> 25:53.385
‐ Well, Cody, your blades
held up relatively well.

25:53.385 --> 25:55.179
The edges are still sharp.

25:55.179 --> 25:58.098
The very, very point
of both of your knives

25:58.098 --> 26:00.267
<i>have become flat</i>
<i>from the impact,</i>

26:00.267 --> 26:03.187
but I don't see
anything letting go.

26:03.187 --> 26:04.396
Nothing chipped out.

26:04.396 --> 26:05.939
But the biggest issue
I have is this ring.

26:05.939 --> 26:09.568
There is a burr on the inside
of this ring.

26:09.568 --> 26:12.112
<i>That's the sharpest part</i>
<i>of this knife.</i>

26:12.112 --> 26:14.364
It actually tore up
this glove a little bit,

26:14.364 --> 26:16.575
so this could end up
hurting the user

26:16.575 --> 26:18.744
instead of the intended victim.

26:18.744 --> 26:21.038
I mean, it wouldn't have taken
ten seconds to get in there

26:21.038 --> 26:22.081
and get that gone.

26:22.081 --> 26:23.457
But blades held up really well.

26:23.457 --> 26:25.667
You have two working karambits
at the end of this.

26:25.667 --> 26:27.753
Good job.
‐ Thank you very much.

26:27.753 --> 26:30.214
‐ Good job.

26:30.214 --> 26:32.716
‐ Well, gentlemen,
we're not done yet.

26:32.716 --> 26:33.717
I give you to Doug.

26:33.717 --> 26:37.262
<i>[ominous music]</i>

26:37.262 --> 26:40.724
‐ Welcome to the sharpness
test: the meat slice.

26:40.724 --> 26:42.101
<i>To find out how sharp</i>
<i>your weapons are,</i>

26:42.101 --> 26:44.603
I will take your karambits
and deliver some slashes

26:44.603 --> 26:46.605
and thrusts on these meats.

26:46.605 --> 26:48.440
Ashley, you're up first.
You ready for this?

26:48.440 --> 26:49.733
‐ Very much so.

26:49.733 --> 26:51.902
‐ Let's do this, sir.

26:51.902 --> 26:54.780
<i>‐ I'm worried about</i>
<i>the sharpness of my blades.</i>

26:54.780 --> 26:56.573
<i>I wish that I had</i>
<i>had more time</i>

26:56.573 --> 26:58.909
<i>to get my blades</i>
<i>nice and sharp.</i>

26:58.909 --> 27:00.619
This could be me going home.

27:00.619 --> 27:02.287
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:06.416 --> 27:09.294
<i>[rock music]</i>

27:09.294 --> 27:16.301
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:31.817 --> 27:33.527
[exhales]

27:33.527 --> 27:34.695
‐ All right, Ashley.

27:34.695 --> 27:37.155
First up, one karambit
is comfortable.

27:37.155 --> 27:38.866
The straighter one here
with a handle

27:38.866 --> 27:41.368
bothers my index finger
when I'm maneuvering

27:41.368 --> 27:42.661
with your blade.

27:42.661 --> 27:44.872
Now, despite losing your tips,

27:44.872 --> 27:46.415
the angle in the side
you have here

27:46.415 --> 27:47.749
is great for thrusting.

27:47.749 --> 27:50.294
It thrusts deep with every
penetration in there.

27:50.294 --> 27:53.964
But more importantly,
for this test, it will cut.

27:53.964 --> 27:55.549
‐ Thank you.
‐ Great job.

27:55.549 --> 27:57.175
‐ [exhales]

27:57.175 --> 27:59.177
‐ All right, Doug.
You're up next.

27:59.177 --> 28:01.388
You ready, sir?
‐ Yeah, absolutely.

28:01.388 --> 28:02.389
‐ Let's do this.

28:02.389 --> 28:04.057
<i>‐ I wanna get this over with.</i>

28:04.057 --> 28:05.767
<i>I'm ready.</i>

28:05.767 --> 28:07.686
<i>I'm nervous about 'em,</i>
<i>and I'm just hoping that</i>

28:07.686 --> 28:09.271
they're sharp enough to cut.

28:09.271 --> 28:12.232
<i>[upbeat rock music]</i>

28:12.232 --> 28:13.734
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:13.734 --> 28:15.694
[metallic clang]

28:15.694 --> 28:22.701
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:36.298 --> 28:38.550
‐ That was awesome.
‐ Holy hell, dude.

28:38.550 --> 28:41.720
‐ Thanks. [exhales]
‐ All right, Doug.

28:41.720 --> 28:43.680
These are definitely
sharper edges.

28:43.680 --> 28:46.308
As you can see,
it cuts deep into the meat.

28:46.308 --> 28:48.060
Despite missing the tips
in there,

28:48.060 --> 28:51.313
they puncture nicely in terms
of damage and sharpness.

28:51.313 --> 28:54.107
You karambits will cut.
Good job.

28:54.107 --> 28:55.776
‐ Thank you very much.

28:55.776 --> 28:57.027
‐ All right, Cody.
It's your turn.

28:57.027 --> 28:58.695
You ready to dance?
‐ Go to town.

28:58.695 --> 29:01.740
‐ Let's do this.
<i>‐ I'm very excited, nervous.</i>

29:01.740 --> 29:04.451
Doug Marcaida has wielded
a lot of karambits before,

29:04.451 --> 29:06.203
<i>and he know how</i>
<i>they should feel.</i>

29:06.203 --> 29:09.206
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

29:09.206 --> 29:12.000
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:12.000 --> 29:14.461
<i>Watching Doug and how</i>
<i>he holds the karambits,</i>

29:14.461 --> 29:17.464
<i>I think that that handle is</i>
<i>so important.</i>

29:17.464 --> 29:20.133
<i>Because if you see him</i>
<i>working that blade,</i>

29:20.133 --> 29:21.927
<i>it's just an extension</i>
<i>of his body.</i>

29:21.927 --> 29:28.934
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:31.812 --> 29:35.565
‐ Cody, as you can see,
what it did to the meat,

29:35.565 --> 29:37.025
that would do to my finger.

29:37.025 --> 29:41.029
As beautiful
as your blades are,

29:41.029 --> 29:44.950
the handle should never cut
the end user.

29:44.950 --> 29:48.120
I can't use a knife like this.
‐ I understand.

29:48.120 --> 29:50.455
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:50.455 --> 29:52.958
‐ Cody, a weapon cannot hurt
the end user.

29:52.958 --> 29:55.419
We cannot test your weapon,

29:55.419 --> 29:57.462
and therefore, I'd like
to invite you to come forward

29:57.462 --> 30:00.298
and shake our hands and then
please leave The Forge.

30:00.298 --> 30:01.299
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:01.299 --> 30:03.135
I'm so sorry, man.
‐ It's all good.

30:03.135 --> 30:05.512
‐ Thank you
for the opportunity.

30:05.512 --> 30:08.640
<i>I'm going home because</i>
<i>I overlooked one tiny detail,</i>

30:08.640 --> 30:11.518
<i>and you just can't have</i>
<i>a blade that hurts its user.</i>

30:11.518 --> 30:13.979
I was not able to prove
what I wanted to prove.

30:13.979 --> 30:17.065
I did wanna become
"Forged in Fire" champion.

30:17.065 --> 30:18.400
<i>If I could do anything</i>
<i>differently,</i>

30:18.400 --> 30:20.569
I would have ten seconds
to take a file

30:20.569 --> 30:22.487
to that [bleep] burr.

30:22.487 --> 30:25.574
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:25.574 --> 30:27.868
‐ Doug, Ashley,
congratulations.

30:27.868 --> 30:29.703
Your karambits
have landed you guys

30:29.703 --> 30:31.496
into the final round
of this competition.

30:31.496 --> 30:32.748
Good job.

30:32.748 --> 30:34.207
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

30:34.207 --> 30:35.709
to make one of these.

30:35.709 --> 30:38.962
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

30:38.962 --> 30:45.677
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:45.677 --> 30:47.137
The cane sword.

30:47.137 --> 30:49.514
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:49.514 --> 30:51.433
<i>Epitomizing the perfect mix</i>

30:51.433 --> 30:53.393
<i>of Victorian era</i>
<i>high‐class gentlemen</i>

30:53.393 --> 30:55.020
<i>and self‐defense,</i>

30:55.020 --> 30:57.022
<i>the cane sword was</i>
<i>the ultimate combination</i>

30:57.022 --> 30:58.440
<i>of fashion and function.</i>

30:58.440 --> 31:01.485
<i>With crime on the rise</i>
<i>in industrializing cities,</i>

31:01.485 --> 31:03.195
<i>the want</i>
<i>for clandestine blades</i>

31:03.195 --> 31:05.405
<i>for upper‐class citizens</i>
<i>exploded.</i>

31:05.405 --> 31:07.866
<i>Easily concealed</i>
<i>in a fashionable cane,</i>

31:07.866 --> 31:09.534
<i>the deadly weapon could</i>
<i>be sprung</i>

31:09.534 --> 31:11.411
<i>by just a click of a button.</i>

31:11.411 --> 31:12.954
<i>Ranging in length</i>
<i>from a dagger</i>

31:12.954 --> 31:14.247
<i>to a full‐fledged sword,</i>

31:14.247 --> 31:16.416
<i>these thin,</i>
<i>razor‐sharp weapons were meant</i>

31:16.416 --> 31:17.959
<i>to deliver quick,</i>
<i>lethal damage</i>

31:17.959 --> 31:19.586
<i>with piercing stabs</i>

31:19.586 --> 31:21.963
<i>while the wooden cane sheath</i>
<i>could also inflict</i>

31:21.963 --> 31:24.049
<i>blunted strikes</i>
<i>on an attacker.</i>

31:24.049 --> 31:26.384
<i>While cane swords have</i>
<i>long gone out of style,</i>

31:26.384 --> 31:28.303
<i>these stealthy weapons</i>
<i>still have their place</i>

31:28.303 --> 31:31.807
<i>in many movies, including</i>
<i>"Who Framed Roger Rabbit."</i>

31:31.807 --> 31:34.518
Gentlemen, make sure that
your blades fall within

31:34.518 --> 31:36.186
the following parameters.

31:36.186 --> 31:37.479
<i>The length of your blade</i>
<i>must be</i>

31:37.479 --> 31:39.523
<i>between 28 and 30 inches</i>
<i>in length.</i>

31:39.523 --> 31:42.025
<i>It must have a cane pommel,</i>
<i>or handle.</i>

31:42.025 --> 31:45.320
The sheath must also
be included in your build,

31:45.320 --> 31:48.573
<i>and it must have a mechanical</i>
<i>locking mechanism.</i>

31:48.573 --> 31:50.659
‐ I've made some swords,
but nothing like this

31:50.659 --> 31:53.620
and nothing that was gonna be
a cane as well.

31:53.620 --> 31:56.289
<i>This is gonna be another</i>
<i>good challenge.</i>

31:56.289 --> 31:58.375
‐ You'll have four days
at your home forges

31:58.375 --> 32:00.293
in which to complete
this weapon.

32:00.293 --> 32:01.753
At the end of those four days,

32:01.753 --> 32:04.339
you'll present your cane swords
to our expert judges.

32:04.339 --> 32:05.757
And after they've thoroughly
tested them,

32:05.757 --> 32:07.968
they'll call one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

32:07.968 --> 32:10.762
who leaves here with a check
for $10,000.

32:10.762 --> 32:13.098
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in four days.

32:13.098 --> 32:15.600
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:15.600 --> 32:17.769
<i>[exciting rock music]</i>

32:17.769 --> 32:19.271
<i>‐ It's day one.</i>

32:19.271 --> 32:21.439
<i>I'm back in my shop</i>
<i>in Columbus, Ohio,</i>

32:21.439 --> 32:24.359
and I'm gonna start
working on rough blade shape.

32:24.359 --> 32:27.112
<i>This is gonna be a very thin,</i>
<i>very light blade.</i>

32:27.112 --> 32:28.989
<i>I don't wanna have excess</i>
<i>material that's</i>

32:28.989 --> 32:30.532
<i>gonna come back to bite me.</i>

32:30.532 --> 32:32.617
I'm gonna start
with exactly what I need

32:32.617 --> 32:33.660
and work from there.

32:33.660 --> 32:35.495
<i>I can't draw it out too thin.</i>

32:35.495 --> 32:37.956
<i>I'll end up with weird</i>
<i>little weak spots</i>

32:37.956 --> 32:39.791
in the middle,
and that's catastrophic

32:39.791 --> 32:41.459
for a blade.

32:41.459 --> 32:43.086
<i>Just cleaning off</i>
<i>a little bit.</i>

32:43.086 --> 32:45.338
<i>There's some pretty gnarly</i>
<i>scale on it.</i>

32:45.338 --> 32:46.965
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:46.965 --> 32:48.466
<i>I'm checking</i>
<i>and then I'm grinding.</i>

32:48.466 --> 32:51.303
<i>I don't wanna take away</i>
<i>any more than I need to.</i>

32:51.303 --> 32:53.221
<i>Little bit more work</i>
<i>in the forge tomorrow,</i>

32:53.221 --> 32:54.723
<i>a little bit more work</i>
<i>on the grinder,</i>

32:54.723 --> 32:56.933
<i>and then I'll be good</i>
<i>for quench.</i>

32:56.933 --> 32:58.602
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:58.602 --> 33:00.604
‐ I'm gonna do a little
fireball action here

33:00.604 --> 33:02.189
to kick this project off.

33:02.189 --> 33:05.859
<i>I'm a trained professional.</i>
<i>Do not do this at home ever.</i>

33:05.859 --> 33:07.652
Three, two, one...

33:07.652 --> 33:09.404
[blasts]

33:09.404 --> 33:11.031
[laughs]

33:11.031 --> 33:13.575
Fireball.
Let's get this party started.

33:13.575 --> 33:16.328
<i>Feels good to be home</i>
<i>in my home shop.</i>

33:16.328 --> 33:19.331
<i>I'm gonna take this piece</i>
<i>of 5160 and get it in the fire</i>

33:19.331 --> 33:21.208
<i>and get it heated</i>
<i>and get it drawn out.</i>

33:21.208 --> 33:23.793
Little nervous about it,
'cause I only have one piece

33:23.793 --> 33:26.796
<i>of this 5160,</i>
<i>so it's kind of crucial</i>

33:26.796 --> 33:28.256
<i>that I don't screw it up.</i>

33:28.256 --> 33:30.258
I'm a Damascus guy,

33:30.258 --> 33:33.386
<i>so I'm gonna use the Damascus</i>
<i>for the pommel</i>

33:33.386 --> 33:34.846
<i>and for the burl.</i>

33:34.846 --> 33:37.015
<i>There's no way this piece</i>
<i>is getting out of here</i>

33:37.015 --> 33:38.850
without some Damascus on it.

33:38.850 --> 33:39.851
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:39.851 --> 33:41.311
<i>‐ Starting off day two...</i>

33:41.311 --> 33:43.188
<i>I've gotta do a little bit</i>
<i>more touch‐up work,</i>

33:43.188 --> 33:44.773
and then I should be ready
for a quench.

33:44.773 --> 33:48.944
All I'm really working on is
straightening out any wiggles.

33:48.944 --> 33:50.695
I've still got a couple.

33:50.695 --> 33:54.991
So I'll just hit and check,
back and forth.

33:54.991 --> 33:57.285
Things aren't really truing up
like I'd like,

33:57.285 --> 34:00.830
so I decide I need to just
go into the quench now.

34:00.830 --> 34:02.666
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:02.666 --> 34:04.000
I don't feel any tings.

34:04.000 --> 34:06.086
Comes out of the quench...

34:06.086 --> 34:07.087
[sighs]

34:07.087 --> 34:08.880
And there's definitely a warp.

34:08.880 --> 34:12.008
I feel like I can re‐quench it
maybe once.

34:12.008 --> 34:15.553
Running a second quench,
it's always risky.

34:15.553 --> 34:17.639
<i>It can put a lot of stress</i>
<i>in the steel.</i>

34:17.639 --> 34:20.684
Things can start to move around
in the structure of the steel.

34:20.684 --> 34:21.643
Damn it.

34:21.643 --> 34:23.061
<i>Am I gonna scrap this blade?</i>

34:23.061 --> 34:25.355
Am I gonna start over
or is this gonna work?

34:25.355 --> 34:28.066
I need to just find out now
and get it over with.

34:28.066 --> 34:30.235
<i>[ominous music]</i>

34:34.906 --> 34:37.993
I come out of the quench,
skate a file down it.

34:37.993 --> 34:39.953
<i>A couple spots towards</i>
<i>the handle that</i>

34:39.953 --> 34:42.289
are a little softer,
but I think we're good

34:42.289 --> 34:43.790
to keep moving along.

34:43.790 --> 34:46.668
I feel like I can finally,
a little bit, start to breathe.

34:46.668 --> 34:47.794
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:47.794 --> 34:48.753
<i>‐ I would have liked</i>
<i>to have gotten</i>

34:48.753 --> 34:49.963
<i>a little further yesterday,</i>

34:49.963 --> 34:52.799
<i>but my quench was</i>
<i>very successful.</i>

34:52.799 --> 34:55.427
Daddy likey!
Whoo!

34:55.427 --> 34:57.679
And so, it's mechanism day.

34:57.679 --> 34:59.806
<i>Well, the cane sword is</i>
<i>gonna require</i>

34:59.806 --> 35:02.309
<i>a locking mechanism,</i>
<i>so the sword will</i>

35:02.309 --> 35:04.436
<i>lock properly</i>
<i>in the cane itself.</i>

35:04.436 --> 35:07.272
I'm not really tooled up
to do stuff like this.

35:07.272 --> 35:10.108
<i>This locking mechanism</i>
<i>really is a tricky bastard.</i>

35:10.108 --> 35:12.652
<i>The brass hook slides</i>
<i>into the bolster,</i>

35:12.652 --> 35:14.779
<i>which latches it</i>
<i>and locks the sword</i>

35:14.779 --> 35:16.489
<i>into the cane itself.</i>

35:16.489 --> 35:18.575
<i>And that has to hinge,</i>
<i>because there has to be</i>

35:18.575 --> 35:21.077
<i>a spring underneath it</i>
<i>that will allow the button</i>

35:21.077 --> 35:23.622
<i>to compress down to where</i>
<i>it releases the lock.</i>

35:23.622 --> 35:26.374
<i>And then the spring will push</i>
<i>the hook back up</i>

35:26.374 --> 35:28.126
to lock into place
in the bolster.

35:28.126 --> 35:29.461
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:29.461 --> 35:31.338
Yeah, I got a latch.

35:31.338 --> 35:33.590
All I have to do is
attach my button to it

35:33.590 --> 35:35.800
and tap this in.

35:35.800 --> 35:37.636
I'm on my way.

35:37.636 --> 35:39.054
<i>‐ I've never made</i>
<i>a cane before,</i>

35:39.054 --> 35:42.015
<i>so today I wanna spend</i>
<i>a whole day dedicated to it.</i>

35:42.015 --> 35:44.392
I wanna make sure that this
cane is structurally solid,

35:44.392 --> 35:45.644
in case they're gonna
beat on it.

35:45.644 --> 35:48.730
So my cane is gonna be
a framed construction.

35:48.730 --> 35:52.817
This bit will be in the middle
of two other slabs.

35:52.817 --> 35:54.819
Kinda like this one.

35:54.819 --> 35:57.322
<i>And it'll all</i>
<i>be pinned together</i>

35:57.322 --> 35:59.991
<i>as well as a fair bit</i>
<i>of epoxy.</i>

35:59.991 --> 36:01.993
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:01.993 --> 36:03.203
Beautiful.

36:03.203 --> 36:05.330
I'm taking my cane down
from being a box

36:05.330 --> 36:07.832
<i>to being a hexagonal shape.</i>

36:07.832 --> 36:09.918
It's starting to really look
like something

36:09.918 --> 36:11.670
other than a block of wood.

36:11.670 --> 36:13.713
I'm doing the texturing
on my cane.

36:13.713 --> 36:15.674
It's very similar
to the flint knap that

36:15.674 --> 36:17.342
we did in the round two

36:17.342 --> 36:18.927
on the handles
of our karambits.

36:18.927 --> 36:21.221
All that's left is, I wanna pop
a little linseed oil

36:21.221 --> 36:24.849
on all the wood parts
and...I mean, I'm done.

36:24.849 --> 36:26.142
<i>[upbeat rock music]</i>

36:26.142 --> 36:27.310
<i>‐ Last day.</i>

36:27.310 --> 36:29.521
<i>First thing I have to do</i>
<i>is make a cane.</i>

36:29.521 --> 36:31.189
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:31.189 --> 36:34.109
It's a little wobbly and rough,

36:34.109 --> 36:35.527
but I think
it gives it character.

36:35.527 --> 36:38.780
We're gonna sand it down
really smooth and then oil it.

36:38.780 --> 36:39.989
It'll be great.

36:39.989 --> 36:42.701
This is my Damascus billet
for the pommel.

36:42.701 --> 36:44.202
That's carbon steel,

36:44.202 --> 36:46.204
so carbon steel
doesn't like this.

36:46.204 --> 36:48.915
<i>The Damascus pommel</i>
<i>has to be tapped,</i>

36:48.915 --> 36:51.042
so it'll screw on the bolt that

36:51.042 --> 36:53.086
I've welded into
the tang of the sword.

36:53.086 --> 36:55.964
<i>If I break the tap off</i>
<i>in here, that's it.</i>

36:55.964 --> 36:58.800
Oh, God,
wish I had another tap.

36:58.800 --> 37:01.010
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:01.010 --> 37:02.387
[cracks]

37:02.387 --> 37:05.014
There it is.
Sure enough, it breaks.

37:05.014 --> 37:06.808
[bleep] damn it.

37:06.808 --> 37:10.812
Failure's not an option,
so I'm gonna go to my plan B,

37:10.812 --> 37:13.398
<i>which is building one</i>
<i>out of a piece of rosewood.</i>

37:13.398 --> 37:16.568
<i>It bums me out,</i>
<i>because the rosewood pommel</i>

37:16.568 --> 37:19.070
<i>isn't as pretty</i>
<i>as the Damascus one.</i>

37:19.070 --> 37:21.906
<i>But I'm just gonna have</i>
<i>to settle with the rosewood.</i>

37:21.906 --> 37:23.241
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:23.241 --> 37:24.743
<i>It's gonna be a good weapon.</i>

37:24.743 --> 37:27.829
There we go, button's working.

37:27.829 --> 37:29.706
<i>It'll definitely</i>
<i>hurt somebody,</i>

37:29.706 --> 37:32.751
and if you got a bad leg,
it'll hold you up.

37:32.751 --> 37:34.169
[chuckles]

37:34.169 --> 37:37.172
[birds cawing]

37:37.172 --> 37:40.175
<i>[tense music]</i>

37:40.175 --> 37:42.594
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:42.594 --> 37:44.846
‐ Doug, Ashley, welcome back

37:44.846 --> 37:47.474
and welcome to the frozen
great outdoors.

37:47.474 --> 37:50.018
You guys have had four days
at your home forges

37:50.018 --> 37:51.102
to work on your cane swords.

37:51.102 --> 37:52.937
Doug, how did it go?

37:52.937 --> 37:55.690
‐ It proved to be
a difficult build for me.

37:55.690 --> 37:57.776
<i>I built the blade</i>
<i>out of 5160.</i>

37:57.776 --> 38:00.737
<i>It's a black walnut cane</i>
<i>and handle</i>

38:00.737 --> 38:02.530
<i>with a rosewood pommel.</i>

38:02.530 --> 38:05.366
<i>The bolsters are Damascus.</i>

38:05.366 --> 38:07.285
It was tough.

38:07.285 --> 38:09.287
‐ All right, Ashley,
how'd it go for you?

38:09.287 --> 38:11.372
‐ I kept mine
pretty straight forward.

38:11.372 --> 38:12.749
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:12.749 --> 38:16.628
<i>I did a 5160 blade,</i>
<i>brass pins here and there,</i>

38:16.628 --> 38:20.048
<i>and a copper connector</i>
<i>to a black and white ebony</i>

38:20.048 --> 38:22.634
<i>little stop at the bottom.</i>

38:22.634 --> 38:24.344
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
your weapons will now be

38:24.344 --> 38:25.804
put through a series
of three tests:

38:25.804 --> 38:27.639
a strength test,
a sharpness test,

38:27.639 --> 38:29.349
and up first, the KEAL test.

38:29.349 --> 38:30.391
Doug.

38:30.391 --> 38:32.811
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:32.811 --> 38:34.813
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
welcome to the KEAL test.

38:34.813 --> 38:37.023
The cane sword.
What an elegant way

38:37.023 --> 38:39.901
to walk around
with a concealed weapon.

38:39.901 --> 38:42.195
To find out what kind of lethal
damage your weapon will do,

38:42.195 --> 38:43.530
I will take your cane sword
and deliver

38:43.530 --> 38:45.949
killing slashes and blows
on this ballistics dummy.

38:45.949 --> 38:47.158
Doug, you're up first.
You ready?

38:47.158 --> 38:48.827
‐ I'm ready.
‐ All right, let's do this.

38:48.827 --> 38:50.078
‐ All right.

38:50.078 --> 38:52.080
<i>I'm really nervous</i>
<i>about today's testing.</i>

38:52.080 --> 38:54.207
<i>Anything could go wrong.</i>

38:54.207 --> 38:55.542
I'm hoping to do
as much damage

38:55.542 --> 38:56.960
<i>to the mannequin as possible.</i>

38:56.960 --> 38:59.337
<i>But you know,</i>
<i>I just‐‐no matter what,</i>

38:59.337 --> 39:00.338
<i>I don't want anything</i>
<i>to break.</i>

39:00.338 --> 39:05.093
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:09.180 --> 39:11.391
<i>[exciting music]</i>

39:11.391 --> 39:18.398
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:24.404 --> 39:25.905
[pops]

39:25.905 --> 39:29.534
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:29.534 --> 39:31.119
[squelches]

39:32.370 --> 39:34.205
‐ Are you kidding me?

39:34.205 --> 39:37.417
‐ [laughs]
All right.

39:37.417 --> 39:40.420
‐ All right, Doug, let's talk
about your cane sword.

39:40.420 --> 39:43.089
You have a very sharp edge.

39:43.089 --> 39:46.676
This blade thrusts nicely,
it cuts nicely.

39:46.676 --> 39:49.470
And who knew
such a very slim blade

39:49.470 --> 39:50.722
could do that much damage?

39:50.722 --> 39:52.348
What I love about
your handle right here

39:52.348 --> 39:53.892
is that curved part
right there.

39:53.892 --> 39:56.019
It gives me that flair
that I like

39:56.019 --> 39:58.730
to feel when I'm thrusting
or slashing

39:58.730 --> 40:00.481
and moving a weapon around.

40:00.481 --> 40:02.901
Your weapon sir, will KEAL.

40:02.901 --> 40:04.569
‐ Thank you very much.

40:04.569 --> 40:05.695
‐ All right, Ashley,
it's your turn.

40:05.695 --> 40:07.238
Are you ready, sir?
‐ Absolutely.

40:07.238 --> 40:08.239
‐ Let's do this.

40:08.239 --> 40:11.242
<i>[rock music]</i>

40:11.242 --> 40:12.410
‐ Tough act to follow.

40:12.410 --> 40:13.703
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:13.703 --> 40:15.538
‐ This is the KEAL test,

40:15.538 --> 40:17.332
<i>and a cane sword has to KEAL.</i>

40:17.332 --> 40:19.626
If it doesn't,
this is the end of the line.

40:19.626 --> 40:23.463
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:23.463 --> 40:25.381
[exhales]

40:25.381 --> 40:31.137
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:31.137 --> 40:33.181
‐ Ooh!
<i>[echoing clang]</i>

40:33.181 --> 40:35.224
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

40:35.224 --> 40:37.060
‐ There it was.

40:37.060 --> 40:38.895
‐ Bro, I'm sorry.

40:38.895 --> 40:40.730
‐ It's all right.

40:40.730 --> 40:45.193
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:45.193 --> 40:48.112
‐ All right, Ashley, let's talk
about your cane sword here.

40:48.112 --> 40:50.448
The cross section shows here
that it is kind of coarse,

40:50.448 --> 40:52.742
so it could be
a heat‐tempering issue.

40:52.742 --> 40:55.787
But worse than that,
some of the grinds here

40:55.787 --> 40:59.540
are uneven, and this
was its thinnest spot.

40:59.540 --> 41:02.085
So as you can see,
it's a critical failure.

41:02.085 --> 41:04.545
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:04.545 --> 41:06.798
‐ Well, Ashley, when we have
a tough break on this show,

41:06.798 --> 41:07.966
it's literal.

41:07.966 --> 41:09.801
You suffered
a catastrophic failure.

41:09.801 --> 41:12.053
It cannot continue
in this competition,

41:12.053 --> 41:13.179
and for that reason,
I'd like to invite you

41:13.179 --> 41:14.973
to please leave the range.

41:14.973 --> 41:16.933
‐ It's heartbreaking,

41:16.933 --> 41:19.978
<i>but I am incredibly proud</i>
<i>of the work that I've done.</i>

41:19.978 --> 41:21.813
<i>When I get home,</i>
<i>the first thing I'm gonna do</i>

41:21.813 --> 41:24.273
<i>is make another cane sword.</i>

41:24.273 --> 41:25.608
I...
[sighs]

41:25.608 --> 41:27.360
I gotta do it right
at least once.

41:27.360 --> 41:28.778
That's how it goes.
‐ Tough break.

41:28.778 --> 41:34.325
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:34.325 --> 41:35.994
‐ Doug, congratulations.

41:35.994 --> 41:37.787
You are the new
"Forged in Fire" champion,

41:37.787 --> 41:39.288
and that's a title that
comes with a check

41:39.288 --> 41:40.498
for $10,000.

41:40.498 --> 41:41.499
How do you feel right now?

41:41.499 --> 41:43.668
‐ Uh, $10,000 richer.

41:43.668 --> 41:45.753
[laughter]

41:45.753 --> 41:47.505
‐ All right, come on over here
and shake our hands, brother.

41:47.505 --> 41:49.382
‐ I did it.
I did it!

41:49.382 --> 41:50.383
‐ Good job, Doug.

41:50.383 --> 41:51.843
<i>‐ It's awesome.</i>

41:51.843 --> 41:54.178
This has been one of the best
experiences of my life.

41:54.178 --> 41:56.681
<i>It took me every emotion</i>
<i>possible:</i>

41:56.681 --> 42:00.685
<i>anger, joy,</i>
<i>to just absolute crying.</i>

42:00.685 --> 42:03.062
For anybody out there
that wants to do this,

42:03.062 --> 42:05.523
<i>my suggestion to you</i>
<i>is show up with your A game</i>

42:05.523 --> 42:08.860
and get a lot of sleep
before you come...

42:08.860 --> 42:11.446
[laughing] 'cause you're not
gonna get any until it's over.

42:11.446 --> 42:14.490
<i>[exciting music]</i>

42:14.490 --> 42:18.870
<i>♪ ♪</i>
